Both drug store chains announced Tuesday that starting in the near future, they'll only sell tobacco products to customers 21 and older.
SHOW TRANSCRIPTTwo major drug store chains announced Tuesday that they're raising the minimum tobacco purchase age to 21.
The moves are in response to the FDA targeting retailers for allegedly selling tobacco products to minors.
It said Walgreens was the "top violator", with 22 percent of inspected stores having sold tobacco to underage customers.
Close to 10 percent of Rite Aid stores inspected were in violation.